  "response": "To calculate the daily energy production of a 1 MW solar power plant, we need to consider several factors:\n\n1. Peak Sun Hours: This varies by location, but typically ranges from 4-6 hours per day.\n\n2. Capacity Factor: Solar plants usually operate at 15-25% efficiency.\n\nUsing average values:\n- 1 MW = 1,000 kW\n- Average sun hours: 5 hours\n- Capacity factor: 20%\n\nCalculation:\n1,000 kW \u00d7 5 hours \u00d7 0.20 = 1,000 kWh per day\n\nSo, a 1 MW solar power plant can typically produce around 1,000 units (kWh) of electricity in a whole day.\n\nNote: Actual production can vary based on:\n- Geographic location\n- Weather conditions\n- Panel technology\n- Seasonal variations\n- Panel orientation",
